1 31
2.
On the methods that may be adopted
[underline]for preventing the accidents arising from[/underline]
[underline]explosions of the fire damp in coal[/underline]
[underline]mines. . by Sir. H D.[/underline]
The accidents arising from the explosion
of the fire damp or inflammable gas of
coal mines mixed with atmospherical air
are actually becoming more frequent
& more terrible in the collieries in the
North of England.-
A committee has been for some time
formed at Sunderland for the [insertion]benevolent[/insertion] purpose of
investigating the causes of these accidents
& of searching for means of preventing
them. the consequence of an invitation
from the Rev[superscript]d[/superscript] D[superscript]r[/superscript] Gray are of the
most active members of this committee

[page]58||dnp11032pp|95149054[/page]
2 32
I was induced to turn my attention
to the subject. I went to the North
of England & visited [insertion]some of[/insertion] the principal
collieries in the neighborhood of
Newcastle [deletion]& conversed with some[/deletion]
[deletion]of the most intelligent[/deletion] for the
purpose of ascertaining the [deletion]state[/deletion] [insertion]condition[/insertion] of
the [deletion]collieries[/deletion] [insertion]workings[/insertion] & [deletion]of[/deletion] their ventilation.
- I found the greatest desire to
[deletion]assist in particular[/deletion] [insertion]to assist my enquiries[/insertion] [deletion]both[/deletion] in the
coal owners, [deletion]& in the Inspectors[/deletion]
[deletion]or viewers of the mines[/deletion] & the
